<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Dumbbell-Scapular-External-Rotation">Dumbbell Scapular External Rotation</h3>



<p>The <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/dumbbell-scapular-external-rotation" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">dumbbell scapular external rotation</a> exercise improves posture and helps with stability within the shoulder joint. This stability is necessary for functional movement, and since the shoulder joint is complex, strengthening it is critical. However, proper scapular (shoulder blade) movement can be impeded if <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9246406/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">posture</a> isn’t correct.</p>



<p>The shoulder blades, or scapula, are stabilized by muscles that allow your arms to move through different ranges of motion. These are known as rotator cuff muscles. Dumbbell scapular external rotations target the teres minor and the infraspinatus muscles. On the other hand, the serratus anterior and trapezius play a role in stabilization.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio vimeo-custom"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<iframe loading="lazy" title="72341201-Dumbbell-Standing-Scapular-External-Rotation-(male)_Back_" src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/988714391?dnt=1&amp;app_id=122963" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; fullscreen; picture-in-picture; clipboard-write"></iframe>
</div><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Dumbbell Scapular External Rotation Guide. Video: Aliaksandr Makatserchyk</figcaption></figure>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">How To Do</h4>



<ol>
<li>Begin standing with feet shoulder-width apart. Bring your shoulder blades down and back while engaging the core. Grasp the handles of two dumbbells and bend your elbows to a 90-degree angle. Your palms should be facing the ceiling.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Maintaining a tight core, exhale and rotate your arms out to the sides. Keep your by your sides and squeeze your shoulder blades together. Inhale and bring your arms back to the starting position.</li>
</ol>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Tips&nbsp;</h4>



<ul>
<li>Ensure your shoulder blades stay down and back while not rising toward the ears.</li>



<li>This exercise doesn’t require heavy weight to be effective. Start low and slow, and build as desired.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Aim to keep your elbows close to your body and your upper arm steady for proper form and technique.</li>
</ul>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Optimal Sets And Reps</h4>



